		<title>
		By: Wan		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.vercel.app/jerry-rice#comment-8357</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Wan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 13 Apr 2014 06:58:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5845#comment-8357</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[&quot;Put in a volume of work.&quot;
Consistency is the key to everything. This one is definitely the hardest part of building skills because not many people are consistent. One of the problem in maintaining consistency is the reliance on motivation or moments of inspiration.
Once we’ve set a goal or decided a habit to implement in our life, stick to it and avoid caring about your laziness and the likes, Mini-habits can help in maintaining consistency too.

&quot;Focus on the areas of greatest leverage for your skill.”
I’m still confused about this one. I’ve heard of various opinion for this topic but after reading this post, I guess I’ll stick to focusing on my strength.
&quot;Find ways to continually improve and move the needle forward rather than falling into routines and patterns once we develop adequate skill levels.”
Great point. Pushing beyond our plateau will induce discomfort. I’ve felt this all the time especially when I’m doing something that’s  beyond my level.
Embracing the discomfort, do it anyway, and reflection and evaluation, can help to improve skills rapidly.
Thanks for the post, James. I don’t know who Jerry Rice is, but I can see that he’s someone that can be an inspiration for all of us who want to improve our life.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>&#8220;Put in a volume of work.&#8221;<br />
Consistency is the key to everything. This one is definitely the hardest part of building skills because not many people are consistent. One of the problem in maintaining consistency is the reliance on motivation or moments of inspiration.<br />
Once we’ve set a goal or decided a habit to implement in our life, stick to it and avoid caring about your laziness and the likes, Mini-habits can help in maintaining consistency too.</p>
<p>&#8220;Focus on the areas of greatest leverage for your skill.”<br />
I’m still confused about this one. I’ve heard of various opinion for this topic but after reading this post, I guess I’ll stick to focusing on my strength.<br />
&#8220;Find ways to continually improve and move the needle forward rather than falling into routines and patterns once we develop adequate skill levels.”<br />
Great point. Pushing beyond our plateau will induce discomfort. I’ve felt this all the time especially when I’m doing something that’s  beyond my level.<br />
Embracing the discomfort, do it anyway, and reflection and evaluation, can help to improve skills rapidly.<br />
Thanks for the post, James. I don’t know who Jerry Rice is, but I can see that he’s someone that can be an inspiration for all of us who want to improve our life.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
